@stephenrauch If you pass `query_env` as an attribute, you may end up with extremely complex side-effects. I assume you want to do something like this:

    class SQLAdapter:
        def _expand(self, expression, field_type=None, colnames=False):
            if isinstance(expression, (Expression, Query)):
                first = expression.first
                second = expression.second
                first.query_env = second.query_env = expression.query_env
                op = expression.op
                rv = op(first, second)
                ...

Remember that Expression objects can be reused and the whole structure may be a general acyclic graph, not a tree. If `second` is reused somewhere inside `first` and one of the operations along the way replaces the `query_env` object with something else, calling `expand(first)` will trash `second.query_env` before control flow reaches `expand(second)`. Or vice versa.

